name: SA, PBP2a (20 to 25):
description: If Cefoxitin zone size is between 20mm-25mm perform PBP2a test.

name: SA, Erythromycin
description: Erythromycin can be used to determine susceptibility of azithromycin, clarithromycin and roxithromycin. Inducible clindamycin resistance can be detected by antagonism of clindamycin activity by a macrolide agent. If not detected, then report as susceptible. If detected, then report as resistant and add comment  "Clindamycin may still be used for short-term therapy of less serious skin and soft tissue infections as constitutive resistance is unlikely to develop during such therapy"

name: SS, Norfloxacin
description: The norfloxacin disk diffusion test can be used to screen for fluoroquinolone resistance. Isolates categorised as susceptible to norfloxacin can be reported susceptible to levofloxacin and moxifloxacin. Isolates categorised as non-susceptible should be tested for susceptibility to individual agents.

name: ES, Gentamicin
description: Enterococci are intrinsically resistant to aminoglycosides and aminoglycoside monotherapy is ineffective. There is likely to be synergy between aminoglycosides and penicillins or glycopeptides against enterococci without acquired high-level resistance. All testing is therefore to distinguish between intrinsic and high-level acquired resistance.  Gentamicin can be used to screen for high-level aminoglycoside resistance

name: EB, ESBL screening:
description: If Cefotaxime is <21 mm or Ceftriaxone is <23mm and Ceftazidime is <21mm proceed with ESBL confirmation testing.

name: EB, Meropenem
description: If Ertapenem is <25 mm set up Meropenem and Imipenem discs.

name: EB, Imipenem
description: If Ertapenem is <25 mm set up Meropenem and Imipenem discs.

name: HI, Nalidixic acid
description: Isolates categorised as susceptible to nalidixic acid can be reported susceptible to ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin, moxifloxacin and ofloxacin. Isolates categorised as non-susceptible may have fluoroquinolone resistance and should be tested against the appropriate agent.

name: Susceptible isolates are uncommon. Check for a possible laboratory error.
Non-susceptible isolates are rare. Check for a possible laboratory error.
The isolate is resistant to all tested antibiotics. You may wish to send the isolate to a reference laboratory for additional testing.
This is an uncommon resistance pattern. Check for a possible laboratory error.
This is an important species. Report to relevant public health authorities if appropriate.
Disk diffusion results are not reliable for this organism and antibiotic.
Depending on your area, resistant isolates may be uncommon.
This is an uncommon resistant pattern. The organism may possess the aac 6'1 enzyme.
ESBL-producing Enterobacteriaceae should be reported as resistant for all penicillins, aztreonam, and cephalosporins, with the exception of cephamycins.
Test for the presence of a carbapenemase.

Rare beta-lactamase-negative, ampicillin-resistant (BLNAR) strains of H. influenzae should be considered resistant to amoxicillin-clavulanic acid, ampicillin-sulbactam, cefaclor, cefetamet, cefonicid, cefprozil, cefuroxime, and loracarbef despite app

Rare beta-lactamase-negative, ampicillin-resistant (BLNAR) strains of H. influenzae should be considered resistant to amoxicillin-clavulanic acid, ampicillin-sulbactam, cefaclor, cefetamet, cefonicid, cefprozil, cefuroxime, and loracarbef.
Non-susceptible isolates have not been previously identified.
Trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole is the preferred disk for detection of sulfonamid resistance with N. meningitidis.

The susceptibility of P. aeruginosa isolated from patients with cystic fibrosis can be reliably determined by the disk method, but may require extended incubation up to 24 hours before reporting as susceptible.
Oxacillin-resistant isolates should be considered resistant to all beta-lactam agents.

Isolates of staphylococci that carry the mecA gene or that produce PBP2a should be reported as oxacillin resistant. Oxacillin-resistant isolates should be considered resistant to all beta-lactam agents.
For S. lugdunensis, only the cefoxitin disk should be used.
The cefoxitin disk test is the preferred method for testing staphylococci for oxacillin resistance.
Staphylococcal isolates which appear "non-susceptible" by disk diffusion should be confirmed by MIC testing.
For strains of S. pneumoniae appearing non-susceptible by disk diffusion, you should perform an MIC test for penicillin, meropenem, cefotaxime, and/or ceftriaxone.
Disk diffusion results may not be reliable for this organism and antibiotic.
Isolates may develop resistance during therapy. Testing of repeat isolates may be warranted.
These agents may appear susceptible in vitro but are not effective clinically.
Rifampin should not be used alone for chemotherapy.
Breakpoints presume that clarithromycin will be used in an approved regimen that includes a proton-pump inhibitor or an H2 antagonist.

N. gonorrhoeae isolates with intermediate results with most agents have a documented lower clinical cure rate (85 to 95%) compared to >95% for susceptible strains. For cefmetazole, cefotetan, cefoxitin, and spectinomycin, the impact is unclear.
A nalidixic acid zone<=25mm may correlate with diminished fluoroquinolone susceptibility.
A nalidixic acid MIC >=8 ug/ml may correlate with diminished fluoroquinolone susceptibility.

Azithromycin, minocycline, ciprofloxacin, sulfonamides, and rifampin may be appropriate only for prophylaxis of meningococcal case contacts. Breakpoints do not apply to therapy of patients with invasive meningococcal disease.
Fluoroquinolone-susceptible strains for Salmonella that test resistant to nalidixic acid may be associated with clinical failure or delayed response in patients with extraintestinal salmonellosis.

Routine testing of urine isolates of S. saprophyticus is not advised, because infections respond to concentrations achieved in urine of antimicrobial agents commonly used to treat acute, uncomplicated urinary tract infections.
This isolate is presumed to be resistant based on detection of inducible clindamycin resistance. Clindamycin may still be effective in some patients.
High doses of intravenous penicillins or ampicillin are effective in treating pneumococcal pneumonia due to strains in the intermediate category.
Use of interpretive criteria for non-meningitis requires doses appropriate for serious pneumococcal infections.
Use of cefotaxime or ceftriaxone in meningitis requires therapy with maximum doses.
Penicillin or ampicillin intermediate isolates may require combined therapy with an aminoglycoside for bactericidal action.

Recommendations for intrapartum prophylaxis for Group B streptococci are penicillin or ampicillin. When a Group B streptococcus is isolated from a pregnant woman with severe penicillin allergy, clindamycin and erythromycin should be tested and report
